{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"b8510347-ab98-41a4-91ee-bb13e00d4a04","content":"Here's the modernized version:\n\n```csharp\n[TestMethod]\npublic void CreateUser_NullEmail_ThrowsException()\n{\n    var service = new UserService();\n    Assert.ThrowsExactly<ArgumentNullException>(\n        () => service.CreateUser(null, \"John\"));\n}\n```\n\nKey changes:\n- Remove the `[ExpectedException]` attribute\n- Wrap the throwing call in `Assert.ThrowsExactly<T>(() => ...)`\n\nThis is better because it pinpoints *which line* should throw. With `[ExpectedException]`, any line in the method could throw and the test would still pass, potentially masking bugs.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"b149bffa-df82-4191-b42f-fe92291f14df","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user wants to modernize their MSTest test from using the `[ExpectedException]` attribute to using `Assert.ThrowsExactly`. This is a straightforward code guidance question.","outputTokens":220,"requestId":"BD19:20A50F:1E07DF1:21E82E7:6A07CA74"},"id":"c5bb529d-3646-4ce7-9d2d-db3bedbc0374","timestamp":"2026-05-16T01:38:01.849Z","parentId":"2e18a058-64c6-4811-ba41-d57a02d77c45"}
